SIMPLE: trunnion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trunnion
<hw>Trun"nion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>trognon</ets> the stock, stump, or truck of a tree, F.
<ets>trognon</ets> a core, stalk, fr. <ets>tron</ets> a trunk, stem. Cf.
<er>Trunk</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Gun.)</fld> <def>A cylindrical
projection on each side of a piece, whether gun, mortar, or howitzer,
serving to support it on the cheeks of the carriage. See
<xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Cannon</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Steam Engine)</fld> <def>A gudgeon on each side of
an oscillating steam cylinder, to support it. It is usually tubular, to
convey steam.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Trunnion plate</b></col> <fld>(Gun.)</fld>, <cd>a plate
in the carriage of a gun, mortar, or howitzer, which covers the upper
part of the cheek, and forms a bearing under the trunnion.</cd> --
<col><b>Trunnion ring</b></col> <fld>(Gun.)</fld>, <cd>a ring on a
cannon next before the trunnions.</cd> <mark>[R.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trunnioned</ent>⟦br⟧
